,"id":"42330","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/42330"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a two-day history of right upper quadrant pain, fever, nausea and vomiting. She has a medical history of type 2 diabetes. Her medications list include metformin. On examination, she appears unwell and jaundiced. Her pulse rate is 110/min,  blood pressure 90/55 mmHg, and temperature is 38\u00b0C. Abdominal examination reveals tenderness in the right subcostal region. Fluid resuscitation is commenced and she is given intravenous antibiotics.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Chest X-ray","Magnetic resonance cholangiopancreatography (MRCP)","Endoscopic Retrograde Cholangiopancreatography (ERCP)","Ultrasound (USS)","CT scan abdomen"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with right upper quadrant (RUQ) pain and tenderness, fever and jaundice. This is the eponymous Charcot\u0027s Triad: the classical presentation of acute cholangitis. These are key features of extra-hepatic biliary obstruction. Jaundice is uncommon with acute cholecystitis alone, occurring in around 10%. The jaundice can reflect either the severity of the transmural inflammatory response or (rarely) impaction of a stone in the cystic duct with subsequent compression of the common bile duct (Mirizzi syndrome).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe simplest, quickest, cheapest and least invasive investigation is a transabdominal \u003Cstrong\u003Eultrasound examination\u003C/strong\u003E. This will confirm the clinical suspicion that the underlying problem is gallstones and that there is biliary obstruction. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003EMRCP\u003C/strong\u003E is more sensitive but time consuming, expensive and unlikely to give more information than an USS in the majority of cases. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EERCP\u003C/strong\u003E may ultimately be required as most patients will require biliary decompression especially in the presence of sepsis such as in this case. But it is invasive and not without associated morbidity, it is reserved for once the diagnosis has been made. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eabdominal CT scan\u003C/strong\u003E is beneficial when ultrasound does not result in a diagnosis and another pathology is suspected. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Echest X-ray\u003C/strong\u003E is useful to help exclude a pneumoperitoneum such as occurs with a perforated peptic ulcer, it is not an unreasonable first investigation but unlikely to yield a diagnosis in this case.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["When a patient presents with RUQ pain, extra-hepatic biliary obstruction should be investigated.","Transabdominal ultrasound is considered the most useful investigation for gallstones, especially considering factors such as it is relatively inexpensive, readily available, and does not expose the patient to radiation."],"references":["Jones MW, Genova R, O\u0027Rourke MC. Acute Cholecystitis. In: StatPearls [Online]. 2021. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK459171/","Kiriyama S, Kozaka K, Takada T, Strasberg SM, Pitt HA, Gabata T, et al. Tokyo Guidelines 2018: Diagnostic criteria and severity grading of acute cholangitis (with videos). J Hepatobiliary Pancreat Sci. 2018;25(1):17-30. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29032610/","Yip AW, Chow WC, Chan J, Lam KH. Mirizzi syndrome with cholecystocholedochal fistula: preoperative diagnosis and management. Surgery. 1992;111(3):335-8. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/1542859/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"27353"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"764"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"27353","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/27353"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-02-07T15:23:05+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-02-07T15:23:05+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"764"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"42330"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"descrip